19. “For your obedience has spread abroad to all.’' The second reason of the admonition is taken from the adjunct of the fame of the obedience which they had hitherto rendered to the gospel. The force of the argument from this is—that the more celebrated their obedience had been, the more notorious, and attended with the greater cause of offence, would be their declension and apos- tacy to the side of the schismatic. The apostle therefore ‘here thus reasons :-— ἡ

‘ Those, the obedience rendered by whom to the gospel of peace is celebrated, should, most of all, beware of divisions contrary to the peace of the gospel:

‘ But the obedience hitherto rendered to the gospel of peace by you who are at Rome, has become celebrated and known to all:

‘Therefore you, above others, should beware of divisione, and shun the authors of divisions.'

The proposition is obvious.
